"Biasi C., Rusalimova O., Meyer H., Kaiser C., Wanek W., Barsukov P., Junger H., Richter A.","Temperature-dependent shift from labile to recalcitrant carbon sources of arctic heterotrophs",2005,"Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry","19","11",,"1401","1408",,,10.1002/rcm.1911,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-20444370276&partnerID=40&md5=2df05c8ddd385a0086872ad0cc9b0d87","Institute of Ecology and Conservation Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Vienna, Austria; Institute of Soil Science and Agrochemistry, Russian Academy of Sciences, Siberian Branch, Str. Sovetskaya 18, 630099 Novosibirsk, Russian Federation; Helsinki University, Dating Laboratory, POB 64, 00014 Helsinki, Finland","Biasi, C., Institute of Ecology and Conservation Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Vienna, Austria; Rusalimova, O., Institute of Soil Science and Agrochemistry, Russian Academy of Sciences, Siberian Branch, Str. Sovetskaya 18, 630099 Novosibirsk, Russian Federation; Meyer, H., Institute of Ecology and Conservation Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Vienna, Austria; Kaiser, C., Institute of Ecology and Conservation Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Vienna, Austria; Wanek, W., Institute of Ecology and Conservation Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Vienna, Austria; Barsukov, P., Institute of Soil Science and Agrochemistry, Russian Academy of Sciences, Siberian Branch, Str. Sovetskaya 18, 630099 Novosibirsk, Russian Federation; Junger, H., Helsinki University, Dating Laboratory, POB 64, 00014 Helsinki, Finland; Richter, A., Institute of Ecology and Conservation Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Vienna, Austria","Soils of high latitudes store approximately one-third of the global soil carbon pool. Decomposition of soil organic matter (SOM) is expected to increase in response to global warming, which is most pronounced in northern latitudes. It is, however, unclear if microorganisms are able to utilize more stable, recalcitrant C pools, when labile soil carbon pools will be depleted due to increasing temperatures. Here we report on an incubation experiment with intact soil cores of a frost-boil tundra ecosystem at three different temperatures (2°C, 12°C and 24°C). In order to assess which fractions of the SOM are available for decomposition at various temperatures, we analyzed the isotopic signature of respired CO2 and of different SOM fractions. The δ13C values of CO2 respired were negatively correlated with temperature, indicating the utilization of SOM fractions that were depleted in 13C at higher temperatures. Chemical fractionation of SOM showed that the water-soluble fraction (presumably the most easily available substrates for microbial respiration) was most enriched in 13C, while the acid-insoluble pool (recalcitrant substrates) was most depleted in 13C. Our results therefore suggest that, at higher temperatures, recalcitrant compounds are preferentially respired by arctic microbes. When the isotopic signatures of respired CO2 of soils which had been incubated at 24°C were measured at 12°C, the δ13C values shifted to values found in soils incubated at 12°C, indicating the reversible use of more easily available substrates. Analysis of phospholipid fatty acid profiles showed significant differences in microbial community structure at various incubation temperatures indicating that microorganisms with preference for more recalcitrant compounds establish as temperatures increase. In summary our results demonstrate that a large portion of tundra SOM is potentially mineralizable. Copyright © 2005 John Wiley &amp; Sons, Ltd.",,"carbon; carbon dioxide; fatty acid; Arctic; biomass; bioremediation; cell respiration; chemistry; conference paper; ecosystem; fractionation; greenhouse effect; metabolism; microbiology; soil; temperature; Arctic Regions; Biodegradation, Environmental; Biomass; Carbon; Carbon Dioxide; Cell Respiration; Chemical Fractionation; Ecosystem; Fatty Acids; Greenhouse Effect; Soil; Soil Microbiology; Temperature",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Fatty Acids; Soil",,,,"(2001) IPCC Third Assessment Report: Climate Change 2001. Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Cambridge University Press: Cambridge; Trumbore, S.E., Chadwick, O.A., Amundsen, R., (1996) Science, 272, p. 393; Giardina, C.P., Ryan, M.G., (2000) Nature, 404, p. 858; Liski, J., Ilvesniemi, H., Makela, A., Westman, C.J., (1999) Ambio, 28, p. 171; Rustad, L., (2001) Nature, 413, p. 578; Luo, Y.Q., Wan, S.Q., Hui, D.F., Wallace, L.L., (2001) Nature, 413, p. 622; Melillo, J.M., Steudler, P.A., Aber, J.D., Newkirk, K., Lux, H., Bowles, F.P., Catricala, C., Morrisseau, S., (2002) Science, 298, p. 2173; Knorr, W., Prentice, I.C., House, J.I., Holland, E.A., (2005) Nature, 433, p. 298; Ågren, G.I., (2000) Ambio, 29, p. 55; Davidson, E.A., Trumbore, S.E., Amundson, R., (2000) Nature, 408, p. 789; Parton, W.J., Schimel, D.S., Cole, C.V., Ojima, D.S., (1987) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 51, p. 1173; Sjogersten, S., Turner, B.L., Mahieu, N., Condron, L.M., Wookey, P.A., (2003) Global Change Biol., 9, p. 759; Townsend, A.R., Vitousek, P.M., Desmarais, D.J., Tharpe, A., (1997) Biogeochemistry, 38, p. 1; Schimel, D.S., Braswell, B.H., Holland, E.A., McKeown, R., Ojima, D.S., Painter, T.H., Parton, W.J., Townsend, A.R., (1994) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 8, p. 279; Weintraub, M.N., Schimel, J.P., (2003) Ecosystems, 6, p. 129; Amundsen, R., Stern, L., Baidsen, T., Wang, Y., (1998) Geoderma, 82, p. 83; Cheng, W., (1996) Plant Soil, 183, p. 263; Ekblad, A., Nyberg, G., Hogberg, P., (2002) Oecologia, 131, p. 245; Santruckova, H., Bird, M.I., Lloyd, J., (2000) Funct. Ecol., 14, p. 108; Bol, R., Bolger, T., Cully, R., Little, D.J., (2003) Plant Nutr. Soil Sci., 166, p. 300; Andrews, J.A., Matamala, R., Westover, K.M., Schlesinger, W.H., (2